        {
          "question": "<p>Write any two properties of a magnet.</p>",
          "id": 477508,
          "options_data": [],
          "solution_data": [
            {
              "id": 255265,
              "solution": "<p>Two properties of magnets are given below:</p>\r\n\r\n<ol start=\"1\" style=\"list-style-type: lower-roman;\">\r\n\t<li>A magnet has two poles: North pole and South pole.</li>\r\n\t<li>Like&nbsp;poles repel each other and unlike poles attract each other.</li>\r\n</ol>"
            }
          ],
          "num_solutions_data": [],
          "alternate_solutions_data": [],
          "marks": 0,
          "youtube_id": "",
          "order": 5,
          "sub_order": null,
          "name": "5"
        },
        {
          "question": "<p>Where are poles of a bar magnet located?</p>",
          "id": 72582,
          "options_data": [],
          "solution_data": [
            {
              "id": 19449,
              "solution": "<p>A magnet has two poles, viz. north pole and south pole. The magnetic power is concentrated on the poles of a magnet. When a bar magnet is suspended to move freely, it always points in the north-south direction. The north pole of the magnet points towards the north and the south pole of the magnet points towards the south.</p>"
            }
          ],
          "num_solutions_data": [],
          "alternate_solutions_data": [],
          "marks": 0,
          "youtube_id": "",
          "order": 6,
          "sub_order": null,
          "name": "6"
        },
        {
          "question": "<p>A bar magnet has no markings to indicate its poles. How would you find out near which end is its north pole located?</p>",
          "id": 72583,
          "options_data": [],
          "solution_data": [
            {
              "id": 19450,
              "solution": "<p>When a bar magnet is suspended freely, it always rests in north-south direction. The end pointing towards north is called north seeking end or the north-pole and the end pointing towards south as called south seeking end or the south-pole of the magnet. Usually, north (N) and south (S) poles are marked on the magnets.</p>"
            }
          ],
          "num_solutions_data": [],
          "alternate_solutions_data": [],
          "marks": 0,
          "youtube_id": "",
          "order": 7,
          "sub_order": null,
          "name": "7"
        },
        {
          "question": "<p>You are given an iron strip. How will you make it into a magnet?</p>",
          "id": 72584,
          "options_data": [],
          "solution_data": [
            {
              "id": 19451,
              "solution": "<p>We can convert an iron strip by repeatedly striking it by a bar magnet systematically. Take the iron strip stroke it with one pole of a bar magnet in one direction. When you reach the other end of the iron piece, lift the magnet and bring the same pole back to the starting end of the iron piece. Stroke again, in the same direction. Repeat this process about 30&ndash;40 times. Check whether the iron piece has now become a magnet. If not , continue the process for some more time. Remember the pole of the magnet and the direction of stroking is not to be changed.<br />\r\n<img src=\"https://media-mycbseguide.s3.amazonaws.com/images/quesbank/06/science/image120.jpg\" style=\"height: 174px; width: 200px;\" /></p>"
            }
          ],
          "num_solutions_data": [],
          "alternate_solutions_data": [],
          "marks": 0,
          "youtube_id": "",
          "order": 8,
          "sub_order": null,
          "name": "8"
        },
        {
          "question": "<p>How is a compass used to find directions?</p>",
          "id": 72585,
          "options_data": [],
          "solution_data": [
            {
              "id": 19452,
              "solution": "<p>A compass is usually a small box with a&nbsp; glass cover on it. A magnetised needle is pivoted inside the box, which can rotate freely . The compass also has a dial with directions marked on it. The compass is kept at the place where we wish to know the directions. Its needle indicates the north-south direction when it comes to rest. The compass is then rotated until the north and south marked on the dial are at the two ends of the needle. To identify the north-pole of the magnetic needle, it is usually painted in a different colour.</p>\r\n\r\n<ol start=\"1\" style=\"list-style-type: lower-alpha;\">\r\n\t<li><img src=\"https://media-mycbseguide.s3.amazonaws.com/images/quesbank/06/science/image121.jpg\" style=\"height:144px; width:130px\" /></li>\r\n\t<li><img src=\"https://media-mycbseguide.s3.amazonaws.com/images/quesbank/06/science/image122.jpg\" style=\"height: 149px; width: 150px;\" /></li>\r\n</ol>"
            }
          ],
          "num_solutions_data": [],
          "alternate_solutions_data": [],
          "marks": 0,
          "youtube_id": "",
          "order": 9,
          "sub_order": null,
          "name": "9"
        },
        {
          "question": "<p>A magnet was brought from different directions towards a toy boat that has&nbsp;been floating in water in a tub. Affect observed in each case is stated in Column I. Possible reasons for the observed affects are mentioned in Column II. Match the statements given in Column I&nbsp;with those in Column II.</p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"3\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"width:100%;\">\r\n\t<tbody>\r\n\t\t<tr>\r\n\t\t\t<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><strong>Column I</strong></td>\r\n\t\t\t<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><strong>Column II</strong></td>\r\n\t\t</tr>\r\n\t\t<tr>\r\n\t\t\t<td>(a) Boat gets attracted towards the magnet</td>\r\n\t\t\t<td>(i) Boat is fitted with a magnet with north&nbsp;pole towards its head</td>\r\n\t\t</tr>\r\n\t\t<tr>\r\n\t\t\t<td>(b) Boat is not affected by the magnet</td>\r\n\t\t\t<td>(ii) Boat is fitted with a magnet with south&nbsp;pole towards its head</td>\r\n\t\t</tr>\r\n\t\t<tr>\r\n\t\t\t<td>(c) Boat moves towards the magnet if north&nbsp;pole of the magnet is brought near its head</td>\r\n\t\t\t<td>(iii) Boat has a small magnet fixed along its length</td>\r\n\t\t</tr>\r\n\t\t<tr>\r\n\t\t\t<td>(d) Boat moves away from the magnet when the north pole is brought near its head</td>\r\n\t\t\t<td>(iv) Boat is made of magnetic material</td>\r\n\t\t</tr>\r\n\t\t<tr>\r\n\t\t\t<td>(e) Boat floats without changing its direction</td>\r\n\t\t\t<td>(v) Boat is made up of non-magnetic material</td>\r\n\t\t</tr>\r\n\t</tbody>\r\n</table>",
          "id": 472667,
          "options_data": [],
          "solution_data": [
            {
              "id": 253135,
              "solution": "<p>The correct order of match is (a)-(iv), (b)-(v), (c)-(ii), (d)-(i), (e)-(iii).</p>"
            }
          ],
